05082nam a22008175i 9789633861158DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222016hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338611587 a10.1515/97896338611582doi  a(DE-B1597)633484  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aDX145b.S87 2015 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a323.11914/972231 aSurdu, Mihai, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThose Who Count :bExpert Practicies of Roma Classification /cMihai Surdu. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of tables -- tList of abbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Epistemic and Political Classifications -- tChapter 2 Ethnicity Theories and Research Practices -- tChapter 3 Disciplinary Traditions in the Study of Roma -- tChapter 4 Ethnicity Inscriptions in Censuses and Surveys -- tChapter 5 Influencers of Academic and Expert Discourse about Roma -- tChapter 6 Case Studies on Roma-related Discourse -- tChapter 7 Visual Depictions of Roma in Expert Publications -- tConclusions -- tBibliography -- tName index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThose Who Count scrutinizes the scientific and expert practices of Roma classification and counting, and the politics of Roma-related knowledge production. The book takes a historical perspective on Roma group construction, both as an epistemic object and a policy target, with a focus on the expert discourse of the last two decades. The book argues that knowledge production on Roma is neither objective nor disinterested but rather is co-produced by political and academic actors driven by organizational interests with rather narrow disciplinary research traditions, as well as by political manifestos. The result of such co-production is a negative Roma public image circulating well beyond the expert discourse which reinforces stereotypes held by society at large. The case studies and examples presented in the book show that the state-led population census, policy related surveys, as well as academic and scientific research, together craft an essentialized Roma identity. The recently reemerged Roma-related genetic research imports assumptions, classifications, and narrations from the social sciences and contributes through sampling strategies, interpretation of data, and generalization to reify and pathologize Roma ethnicity. Roma are relegated by experts to several types of determinism: to a social category, to a frozen culture, and to a homogenous biologized entity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCensus. 0aClassificationxPolitical aspectsxEurope. 0aClassificationxPolitical aspectszEurope. 0aClassificationxSocial aspectsxEurope. 0aClassificationxSocial aspectszEurope. 0aEthnicityxGovernment policyxEurope. 0aEthnicityxGovernment policyzEurope. 0aPublic opinionxEurope. 0aPublic opinionzEurope. 0aRomaniesxGovernment policy. 0aRomaniesxPublic opinion. 0aRomaniesxResearch. 0aSocial surveysxPolitical aspectsxEurope. 0aSocial surveysxPolitical aspectszEurope. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh  aClassification, Ethnicity, Minorities, Roma studies, Romanies, Social policy, Social surveys, Stereotypes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2016z978311078053640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963386115840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633861158423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633861158/original  a978-3-11-078